@article{Kreulen1975,
abstract = {Wildebeest (Connochaetes taurinus hecki Neumann) occupancy on the Serengeti plains is not uniform (Fig. 1). The east and centre are more utilized than the west (Penny- cuick, 1974; Watson {\&} Kerfoot, 1964), despite a shorter timespan of ‘suitability', i.e. green grass and water availability, due to rainfall and soil type. Anderson {\&} Talbot (1965) have suggested that the function of this habitat selection is related to differences in soil stickiness and in growth stage and form of grasses. Grass height may also be involved, as suggested by findings on feeding adaptations (Bell, 1969) and as grass height is probably related to safety. None of these factors, however, seems to have ultimate importance, firstly because wildebeest move to the east as soon as it provides green grass and water, regardless of the condition of the soil and vegetation in the west (Braun, 1971; Watson {\&} Kerfoot, 1964), and secondly because the differences in grass height and structure which often but not always exist, are largely the result of the difference in grazing pressure (Schmidt, 1975). A conceivable function of the selective use of the east is the acquisition of an adequate supply of certain nutrients, particularly because a high demand exists, for lactation, during the utilization period of the plains. Preliminary evaluation of grass productivity and protein data of Braun (1973) and of protein, energy, digestibility, Na, Ca, Mg, P, Co, Cu, Mo, Zn and F data from grass and drinking water collected by the author, revealed that calcium indeed might be involved, but none of the other nutrients. The analysis of the Ca data is therefore presented below.},
